snippet.textDisplay:
Regarding evolutionary theories: A little bit of both. It gained a browsing advantage and started developing longer necks to compete with other herbivores, which in turn gave it an unintended advantage in selecting mates. Over time, competition for ground based plants became less fierce, but sexual selection was still at play, encouraging longer and longer necks. The gene is given to both male and female offspring, so while the males might not be selecting for long-necked females, giraffe fathers are almost exclusively long necked, having long necked children of both gender.
Another thing: Their general height gives them an advantage against predators too: they can kick with surprising amount of power, able to crack a lions skull with a well placed hoof, or trample them to death. Being extra tall also makes it much tougher for the lion to actually kill it in general too: they have to literally climb up the back and attempt to topple it or exhaust it, as their necks are too thick to just break like most animals.
